[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mPriority breakdown: 0 critical, 2 high, 11 medium, 9 low. [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe verdict is PASS[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m because the HIGH count (2) is at or below the > 3 = FAIL threshold and there are no CRITICAL findings. The two HIGH findings are localized correctness-and-compliance gaps that the prose elsewhere in the recipe correctly diagnoses with TODO references already in place; closing them brings the architecture up to the standard the recipe text claims and matches the chapter pattern from 5.1-5.8. Recipe 5.9 is the chapter's third Complex-tier recipe (after 5.7 and 5.8), and its successful execution at the four-star complexity level (national-scale federated identity resolution as a federation-of-federations under a maturing trust framework, QHIN-credential as federation-trust-anchor with dual-control rotation ceremony, cross-network matching tolerance as separately-calibrated-from-internal-tolerance with information-blocking-compliance-stakes, per-jurisdiction sensitivity overlay with per-hop enforcement and audit reconstruction, seven-stage architecture with inbound-and-outbound query handling plus document retrieval plus cross-cutting concerns, eleven Honest Take observations on operational reality including QHIN-onboarding-as-starting-line-not-finish-line, twelve-extension Variations including QHIN-operator architecture and FHIR-based exchange migration and patient-mediated access through Patient Access API and federated analytics extension and PPRL-and-TEFCA integration) raises the bar for the remaining one Complex-tier entry (5.10 deceased-patient resolution) that follows.[K
