[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    57[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m3[38;2;191;97;106m.[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe response-consolidator Lambda validates each responder's signature against the responder's known public key.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The Step 5 pseudocode validates the responder's signature against the responder's public-signing-key version (with the previous version included during rotation) and validates the per-response attribution chain. But the architecture does not specify how the responder's public-signing-key is provisioned at the participant, how rotation events from the QHIN's framework are propagated to the participant, or how the rejection semantics for misconfigured rotations interact with the response-window expiration. A misconfigured rotation (the participant's responder-key store falls behind the federation's actual rotation cadence; the responder's signature is rejected during the cutover; the response-window expires before the participant can re-validate against the rotated key) silently drops valid responses, which the user perceives as a partial-result presentation that the user cannot disambiguate.[K
